data.content:
Three breaking changes in EF Core 10 hit your code:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — now accepts a regular lambda, not an expression tree

Your manual `Expression.Lambda`/`Expression.Call` tree **won't compile** because the new overload takes `Func<…>` instead of `Expression<Func<…>>`. Replace it with the vastly simpler form:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

No expression-tree construction needed at all — conditionals work inline now.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two changes

**a) Sibling uniquification.** `ShippingAddress.Street` and `BillingAddress.Street` previously mapped to the **same** column silently (data corruption risk). EF 10 auto-appends a numeric suffix (`Street`, `Street1`). To keep the old names or choose explicit ones:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street"));
});
```

**b) Nested full-path naming.** `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` was previously mapped to column `BillingAddress_City`; it now becomes `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. To preserve the old name:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

⚠️ Both of these **will generate migrations** that rename columns. If you have an existing database, either set explicit `HasColumnName` to match your current schema, or plan the migration carefully.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method gained a `string logCommandText` parameter (for redacted SQL logging). Add it:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (constants may be redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for the actual executed SQL
    }
}
```

Update **all** methods on the interface (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) the same way.
